\subsection{Rule matching algorithm%
  \label{rule-matching-algorithm}%
}

Each rule will be tested against each hex of the map. For a rule to match on a
given hex (let name this hex H), the following conditions have to be met:

\begin{itemize}
\item Some random, 1 to 100 number must be inferior to the rule \textquotedbl{}probability\textquotedbl{}

\item If the rule has a position set, it may only match on this very location.

\item All constraints of the rule must match.
\end{itemize}

For a constraint of the rule to match, the following conditions have to be met:

\begin{itemize}
\item The hex corresponding to this constraint must have a type which matches the
constraint's typestring:

\begin{itemize}
\item We define the \textquotedbl{}hex corresponding to this constraint\textquotedbl{} as the hex, on the
map, whose location is the hex H + ofs, ofs being the offset of the
constraint.

\item The hex matches the constraint's typestring if any of those is true.

\begin{itemize}
\item The typestring contains the metacharacter *.

\item The typestring does not start with the character '!', and the hex's
terrain character is included in the typestring.

\item The typestring starts with the character '!', and the hex's terrain
character is \emph{not} included in the typestring.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\item The hex corresponding to this constraint must not have any flag in the
constraint's \textquotedbl{}no\_flag\textquotedbl{} list.

\item The hex corresponding to this contraint must have all the flags present in
the constraint's \textquotedbl{}has\_flag\textquotedbl{} list.
\end{itemize}


\section{WML Reference%
  \label{wml-reference}%
}


\subsection{{[}terrain\_graphics{]}%
  \label{terrain-graphics}%
}

The {[}terrain\_graphics{]} tag represents a terrain graphics rule. It may contain
the following child tags:

\begin{description}
\item[{\hyperref[image]{{[}image{]}}}] \leavevmode 
when an image is defined in a {[}terrain\_graphics{]} tag, it defines a
multi-hex image which will be applied over all tiles of the rule.

\item[{\hyperref[tile]{{[}tile{]}}}] \leavevmode 
adds one (or several) constraints to the rule.

\end{description}

Additionnaly, the {[}terrain\_graphics{]} tag may have the following elements:

\begin{description}
\item[{\texttt{x} and \texttt{y}}] \leavevmode 
format: <number>

Specifies the coordinates at which this rule can match. A rule which has
x-y coordinates may only match at this position in the map, and nowhere
else.

\item[{\texttt{probability}}] \leavevmode 
format: <number>

A number from 0 to 100. Means that this rule will only match, when all
other conditions are met, if a random number from 0 to 100 is inferior to
the \texttt{probability} value. Obviously, 0 means this rule will never match,
and 100 means this rule will always match if all other conditions are met.

\item[{\texttt{precedence}}] \leavevmode 
format: <number>

An optional tag which allows to specify in which order rules are to be
tested. Generally, rules are tested in the order they are defined. However,
rules with a lower precedence will always de tested before rules with
higher precedence.

\item[{\texttt{map}}] \leavevmode 
format: see below

A string, generally a multi-line one, graphically representing the
constraints of this rule. Maps are a shorthand notation to defining several
constraints using the \hyperref[tile]{{[}tile{]}} element. Those have a special structure; see
below (\hyperref[map-format]{Map Format}.)

\item[{\texttt{set\_flag}}] \leavevmode 
Defining a \texttt{set\_flag} element in a rule is identical to defining it on
each constraint of this rule.

\item[{\texttt{has\_flag}}] \leavevmode 
Defining a \texttt{has\_flag} element in a rule is identical to defining it on
each constraint of this rule.

\item[{\texttt{no\_flag}}] \leavevmode 
Defining a \texttt{no\_flag} element in a rule is identical to defining it on
each constraint of this rule.

\item[{\texttt{rotations}}] \leavevmode 
format: <r0> \textquotedbl{},\textquotedbl{} <r1> \textquotedbl{},\textquotedbl{} <r2> \textquotedbl{},\textquotedbl{} <r3> \textquotedbl{},\textquotedbl{} <r4> \textquotedbl{},\textquotedbl{} <r5>

<r0> to <r5> being (usually short) strings.

Specifies that this {[}terrain\_graphics{]} element does not define an actual
rule, but will serve as a template for creating up to 6 rotated rules.

Template rules are defined like normal rules, except that flags and image
filenames may contain template strings of the form \texttt{@Rn}, n being a
number from 0 to 5.

A template rule will generate 6 rules, which are similar to the
template, except that:

\begin{itemize}
\item The map of constraints of this rule will be rotated by an angle, of 0 to
5 pi / 6

\item On the rule which is rotated to 0rad, the template strings @R0, @R1, @R2,
@R3, @R4, @R5, will be replaced by the corresponding r0, r1, r2, r3, r4,
r5 variables given in the rotations= element.

\item On the rule which is rotated to pi/3 rad, the template strings @R0, @R1,
@R2 etc. will be replaced by the corresponding \emph{r1, r2, r3, r4,
r5, r0} (note the shift in indices).

\item On the rule rotated 2pi/3, those will be replaced by r2, r3, r4, r5, r0,
r1 and so on.
\end{itemize}

\end{description}


\subsection{{[}tile{]}%
  \label{tile}%
}

The {[}tile{]} element, in a {[}terrain\_graphics{]} rule, adds one (or more) new
constraints to a rule. It may contain the following child tags:

\begin{description}
\item[{\hyperref[image]{{[}image{]}}}] \leavevmode 
Defining an {[}image{]} element inside of a {[}tile{]} element will define a
single-hex image which will only be applied to the tile the constraint
applies to.

\end{description}

Additionally, the {[}tile{]} tag may contain the following elements:

\begin{description}
\item[{\texttt{x} and \texttt{y}}] \leavevmode 
format: <number>

Specify the offset of the constraint.

\item[{\texttt{loc}}] \leavevmode 
format: <number>, <number>

An alternative notation for specifying the offset of the constraint.

\item[{\texttt{pos}}] \leavevmode 
format: <number>

Specifies that this {[}tile{]} tag does not define a single constraint, but
instead, acts as a template for all constraints defined, on the map, with
an anchor of the same number (See \hyperref[map-format]{Map format}.)

Only meaningful if the {[}terrain\_graphics{]} parent tag contains a \texttt{map}
element.

\item[{\texttt{type}}] \leavevmode 
format: <string>

Defines the typestring for this constraint. This value represents a list of
characters. For the constraint to match, the corresponding terrain tile's
type must be one of those characters.

This string may contain the metacharacter \textquotedbl{}*\textquotedbl{} meaning \textquotedbl{}all terrains\textquotedbl{}, and
the metacharacter \textquotedbl{}!\textquotedbl{}, meaning \textquotedbl{}all terrains except those present in the
list.\textquotedbl{}

\item[{\texttt{set\_flag}}] \leavevmode 
format: <flag> {[} \textquotedbl{},\textquotedbl{} <flag> {]} +

Specifies that, if the rule which contains this constraint matches, the
given flags will be applied to the corresponding terrain tile.

\item[{\texttt{has\_flag}}] \leavevmode 
format: <flag> {[} \textquotedbl{},\textquotedbl{} <flag> {]} +

Specifies that this constraint will only match if the corresponding terrain
tile already has all the given flags.

\item[{\texttt{no\_flag}}] \leavevmode 
format: <flag> {[} \textquotedbl{},\textquotedbl{} <flag> {]} +

Specifies that this constraint will only match if the corresponding terrain
tile does \emph{not} have any of the given flags.

\end{description}


\subsection{{[}image{]}%
  \label{image}%
}

The {[}image{]} element, in the {[}terrain\_graphics{]} element, or in a {[}tile{]}
elements, specify an image which will be added on the terrain, if the
corresponding rule does match.

It may contain the following child tags:

\begin{description}
\item[{\hyperref[variant]{{[}variant{]}}}] \leavevmode 
A time-of-day specific variant of the image.

\end{description}

Images may contain the following elements:

\begin{description}
\item[{\texttt{name}}] \leavevmode 
format: <timed\_image> ( \textquotedbl{},\textquotedbl{} <timed\_image> ) +

<timed\_image> ::= <image\_name> {[} \textquotedbl{}:\textquotedbl{} <timing> {]}

If the name only contains one timed\_image, it will be used as a base to
build the filename of the image corresponding to this {[}image{]} tag, with
\textquotedbl{}images/terrain/\textquotedbl{} prepended, and \textquotedbl{}.png\textquotedbl{} appended.

If the name contains several timed\_images, it will correspond to an
animated image, each timed\_image being a frame of the animation. For each
frame of the animation the <image\_name> part corresponds to the base of the
filename, which will be built as shown above, and the <timing> part will
correspond to the duration, in milliseconds, of this frame.

\item[{\texttt{position}}] \leavevmode 
format: \textquotedbl{}horizontal\textquotedbl{} | \textquotedbl{}vertical\textquotedbl{}

The type of layering this image will use. If set to \textquotedbl{}horizontal\textquotedbl{}, it will
use a layer-based stack model. If set to vertical, images will be assumed
to have an (x,y) position on the screen, and will be layered according to
their coordinates.

\item[{\texttt{layer}}] \leavevmode 
format: <number>

Only meaningful if the \texttt{position} tag was set to \texttt{horizontal}. Images
with an horizontal position will be drawn, lower layer to upper layer,
without taking their position into account.

\item[{\texttt{base}}] \leavevmode 
format: <number> \textquotedbl{},\textquotedbl{} <number>

Only meaningful if the \texttt{position} tag was set to \texttt{vertical}. Specifies
the coordinates of the \textquotedbl{}base\textquotedbl{} of the image, which is, the imaginary pixel
at which the image reaches the \textquotedbl{}floor\textquotedbl{}, relative either to the top-left
corner of the rule, or to the top-left corner of the constraint hex,
depending on whether the image applies to a rule, or to a constraint.

\end{description}


\subsection{{[}variant{]}%
  \label{variant}%
}

{[}variant{]} tags represent a time-of-day-specific version of an image. Variants
may contain the following elements:

\begin{description}
\item[{\texttt{tod}}] \leavevmode 
format: <string>

The identifier of the time-of-day this variant applies to. When the turn's
top is equal to this, the \textquotedbl{}name\textquotedbl{} element of this variant will replace the
\textquotedbl{}name\textquotedbl{} element of the parent image.

\item[{\texttt{name}}] \leavevmode 
format: <timed\_image> ( \textquotedbl{},\textquotedbl{} <timed\_image> ) +

<timed\_image> ::= <image\_name> {[} \textquotedbl{}:\textquotedbl{} <timing> {]}

The image string, which will replace the \textquotedbl{}name\textquotedbl{} element of the parent image
on the right time-of-day.

\end{description}


